<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / UK Company News: Difficulties of buy-outs at recs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Regional electricity companies would make suitable candidates for leveraged
buy-outs, though there would be political and regulatory risks, according to
analysts at Hoare Govett, writes David Lascelles.
In a report on the prospects for LBOs at the privatised electricity
companies, the analysts say they enjoy monopoly profits on their
distribution businesses and strong cash flow, which would support buy-outs.
The expiry of the government's golden shares next March will also aid
increased corporate activity by the recs.
But they also question whether investment banks would be willing to arrange
an LBO for a regulated utility which was heavily dependent upon regulatory
decisions, and might become prone to political decisions as the next
election approaches.
In addition, the recs' shareholding in the National Grid Company would have
to be unscrambled before any LBOs could take place.
The analysts conclude: 'Despite their strong financial attractions, we
question whether recs will become the subject of LBOs.'
</TEXT>
