<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BBC1's new comedy series All Night Long, set in a bakery, depends for its
laughs very largely upon character, so when you describe the plot it all
sounds rather slight and banal. In today's episode a local villain turns up
and demands a birthday cake for his mother, but Romanian cake expert Vanda
refuses to make a Black Forest gateau for political reasons .. (8.30). In
today's episode of Frank Stubbs the wide boy promoter who combines the
social graces of Arthur Daley with the subtlety of Max Clifford, finds
himself landed with a dull Tory MP as a client, a man whose most notable
moment came when he was a student, and involved women's underwear (9.00
ITV). In Panorama John Penycate investigates the changing role of police
informers. The claim is that instead of just passing on information about
crimes already committed or planned, informers are now being used by the
police to set up crimes which are then 'solved', thus improving the police
success rate (9.30 BBC1). Best of the day will be Episode 2 of The Singing
Detective, repeated in tribute to the late Dennis Potter (10.10 BBC1).
</TEXT>
