<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / Market opens to rolling settlement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Share trading under the new 10-day rolling settlement system starts today,
the result of a year of effort by the Stock Exchange and its member firms.
Much of the public focus has been on private-client stockbrokers whose
customers are chary of the new system, but the Stock Exchange itself has
undergone frenetic activity to adapt its Talisman settlement system.
According to the Stock Exchange its efforts have paid off. Every Talisman
participant has given assurances that its own system is fully prepared to
cope with rolling settlement.
But until the exchange completes one 10-day settlement period the efficiency
of the system will remain untested.
Under rolling settlement share bargains settle - that is, shares must be
delivered or paid for - 10 business days after each bargain is struck. That
may not sound onerous to an investor in the US, for whom a five-day gap is
the norm, but the London Stock Exchange has traditionally operated two and
three-week settlement periods.
The new system means that stockbrokers, institutions and marketmakers will
have to deliver cash or securities every single business day instead of on
one day at the end of 24 settlement periods each year.
Talisman is the Stock Exchange's internal settlements system, first built in
1977. Market participants broadly give the system high marks for durability
and efficiency in spite of the surge in share turnover since then.
Mr Bernie Till, who runs the system, said: 'Talisman was originally built as
a rolling settlements system.' The alterations from the trading account
system to rolling settlement require the reversal of changes put in place
more than 15 years ago.
To indicate the size of the Stock Exchange's task, Mr Till pointed out that:
Thirty six of the 58 exchange mainframe computer systems and four personal
computer-based systems had to be modified.
Participants - stockbrokers, marketmakers, the registrars who keep records
of share ownership, and institutional investors - had to modify their own
systems to accommodate changes to Settlement Network Interface Specification
(SNIS) records. These are pathways through which the exchange communicates
electronically with participants. Talisman handles more than 200 input and
output SNIS records.
Member firms had the greatest number of changes, modifying 36 SNIS records,
while registrars were required to modify five.
Meanwhile, the exchange said, it spared no effort in informing investors,
both professionals and private individuals, about how life would change for
them.
</TEXT>
<XX>
