<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / Pressure for Tecs in London to merge
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is seeking to trigger mergers among the nine training and
enterprise councils in London, some of which are among the worst performers
in the network of the 82 employer-led organisations according to government
criteria.
Tecs are responsible for delivering the government's main training
programmes in England and Wales.
Chairmen of the London Tecs have been told by Miss Ann Widdecombe, the
employment minister, to review their structures, including making proposals
for mergers. Proposals could include slimming the existing network to four
or five, with a central strategic body, or even one London Tec.
Tecs in London have been striving to work together more closely, but
achievements on programmes such as Business Links, the umbrella bodies for
business advice, have been modest. A few Tecs have even held informal talks
over mergers. Miss Widdecombe is understood not to approve of this because
of its ad hoc nature.
Mr David Hill, chairman of Aztec, a south London Tec, and the capital's
representative on the Tec national council, said: 'The government has asked
me as the regional Tec chairman for London to review, with other London
chairmen, the structure of the nine Tecs.'
It is understood that some London Tec chairmen, who will discuss the matter
at a meeting tomorrow, do not share the minister's interest in structure.
They would prefer any review to look strategically at London's needs and
then consider what structure was most applicable.
Ms Cay Stratton, of the charity Business in the Community, said: 'The
important thing is not to start talking about boundaries but what are the
pan-London and strategic issues.'
Tec difficulties in London are a result of several factors. These include
the complexity of the London labour market, which employs 16 per cent of the
UK workforce, and a historic underfinancing of government-funded training
schemes in the capital.
Management, Page 9
Letters, Page 14
</TEXT>
