<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / Whitehall consultancy use faces big shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A radical reorganisation of the way the government hires consultancies is
recommended in a Whitehall report likely to be published in the next few
days.
The report suggests that the Cabinet Office's efficiency unit should take a
central monitoring role.
The planned shake-up follows the disclosure that the government is spending
more than Pounds 500m a year on outside consultants with little effort to
track spending or assess value for money.
Mr William Waldegrave, public service minister, has accepted advice from Sir
Peter Levene, the prime minister's adviser on efficiency, that the unit
should act as a clearing house for departments planning to use
consultancies.
It will be expected to check the reliability of the consultancy and prevent
duplication in departments by co-ordinating information on consultancies
across Whitehall.
Ministers are concerned that little attempt has been made to find out
whether other departments have done similar work with consultancies that
could be used instead.
While the efficiency unit will not be controlling the use of consultancies,
its central monitoring role is expected to give departments less room for
manoeuvre when commissioning consultants.
The report is also sensitive to the fact that departments and agencies can
identify just Pounds 10m in savings a year by bringing in external
consultants to improve civil service management.
It says that departments do not use consultants only to save money. A direct
comparison of the identifiable savings against the amount spent on
commissioning consultants is misleading, it says.
Civil servants are concerned that they could be accused of re-writing the
report following the disclosure that consultancies are yielding so little in
savings.
They say that they have only been fine tuning the study's conclusions and
have not changed any of the figures.
Every government department will be expected to draw up its own action plan
to deal with the problem. These will be expected to improve the tracking of
expenditure on consultancy and its benefits.
Ministers want civil servants to adopt the best practice of the private
sector by working more closely with consultants to maximise benefits.
A senior Whitehall official said the report aimed to 'change the culture and
practice' in the use of consultancies. 'We are currently spending far too
much on far too little' he said. 'Ministers are determined to have some
control on the spiralling cost of consultancies.'
</TEXT>
