<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / Ministers bow to pressure over forests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government is tomorrow expected to formally shelve its forestry
privatisation plans after overwhelming opposition from backbench MPs,
environmental groups and the public.
But ministers are due to announce reforms that will force woodland managers
to operate on a more commercial basis when they release details of a review
of the Forestry Commission.
The three ministers responsible for woodlands - Mrs Gillian Shephard,
agriculture minister, Mr John Redwood, Welsh secretary, and Mr Ian Lang,
Scottish secretary - will then publish a consultation document on the
proposed restructuring of the commission.
The ministers are expected to suggest a formal separation between Forest
Enterprise, which is a division of the commission responsible for managing
Britain's 1.1m hectares of woodlands, and the commission itself. This will
leave the commission to handle policy and regulation issues.
Forest Enterprise is expected to have its own board of directors along with
tougher financial targets and a requirement to produce more transparent
accounts.
This compromise move is seen by critics as a possible stepping stone towards
privatisation and as such a way of placating the Treasury, which was keen to
generate cash by selling off the nation's woods.
Conservation and recreational groups still fear that forcing Forest
Enterprise to make a profit could lead it to abandon some of its
environmental commitments.
'It may have to revert to planting wall-to-wall sitka spruce, which we would
see as regrettable,' said Mr Alan Mattingly, director of the Ramblers'
Association. This activity would make more money than the current policy of
diversifying tree species and age ranges, he pointed out.
In spite of the government's partial climbdown, forests are expected to
continue to be sold piecemeal. Forest Enterprise is set to double its sales
of woodlands to 15,000 hectares a year next year. By the end of the century
it will have sold 20 per cent of its estate.
The reforms to the way Forest Enterprise is run come as the division is
beginning to break even. Many slow-maturing plantations were established 30
to 40 years ago and are just coming to a point where they can be harvested
to provide a steady stream of income.
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
    P9641 Regulation of Agricultural Marketing.
    P08   Forestry.
</IN>
<XX>
