<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / The end of bossy bosses foreseen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The manager who persists in thinking that he or she is the boss will be
extinct by the year 2001, says a report by the Institute of Management.
The study says that to avoid becoming a dinosaur the manager will have to
become a team leader, earning people's respect rather than giving them
orders.
Managers are just as likely to be women, because female attributes such as
teamworking, consensus management, negotiating, the ability to handle
several projects at a time and interpersonal skills will be more appropriate
by the next century.
The report was based on interviews with senior and middle managers. The
authors said that, contrary to some opinions, individuals in the UK had
recognised the need for life-long training.
Nearly 90 per cent of those surveyed believed that there would be an
increased need to acquire new skills between now and 2001. They believed
that to improve their prospects they needed transferable skills.
Management Development in the Millennium. IM Books, Burston Distribution
Services, Unit 2A, Newbridge Trading Estate, Whitby Road, Bristol BS4 4AX.
Pounds 75 (Pounds 50 for institute members).
Tecs - after dinner, Page 9
</TEXT>
