<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / PIA kicks off by seeking financial views
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An extensive programme of consultation with the financial services industry
is being planned by the Personal Investment Authority, the watchdog to
protect the private investor which becomes operational today.
In the coming months the PIA will ask for views on a range of issues, such
as the registering of all individuals who work in retail financial services,
and training and competence requirements.
Starting work against a background of suspicion and reluctance even among
some of the 3,500-plus organisations which have applied to join, the PIA
believes that relations with those it regulates will have to be an
important, continuing element of its work.
At the same time, it knows it must not become so close to the industry that
it forfeits people's confidence in financial regulation, instead of
reinforcing it.
Some of the issues on which the PIA is planning to consult are inherited
from the Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, and
the existing regulators for the life insurance industry and independent
financial advisers, which the PIA is replacing. Others have arisen from the
wider debate generated by the controversy the PIA has aroused.
The most immediate issues are consultation about how companies and
individuals should disclose on their stationery and advertising that they
come under the new regulator, and the timescale on which this changeover
should take place. A more substantive task is devising and consulting on the
PIA's own training and competence proposals.
The setting up of a register of all individuals working in retail financial
services, one of the recommendations of the cross-party Treasury committee
of MPs, is also to be pursued quickly - with a consultative paper in the
autumn, and the prospect of implementation in the course of next year.
The PIA will consult in the autumn on extensions to the new regime for
giving customers more information about financial products. This regime will
come into effect on January 1, and work is in hand to try to ensure that it
could apply then, not just to life insurance and investment products as
already planned, but also to unit trusts.
Separately, the regulator will seek views on extending the disclosure
requirements to term assurance, policies concerned solely with protection
against particular contingencies and not with investment.
Perhaps the most difficult issue facing the PIA will be the work it takes
over from the SIB in ensuring that compensation is paid to anyone who has
been disadvantaged by following poor advice to take out a personal pension.
Ms Colette Bowe, PIA chief executive, said yesterday: 'Our main work in the
months ahead is to build public confidence in the industry we regulate. We
have big tasks to carry out in disclosure, training and competence and our
ongoing work of monitoring and supervision.'
</TEXT>
