After the press conference, China's Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a
terse statement suggesting that the meeting was 'not necessary' because of
the Sino-British dispute over Hong Kong Governor Chris Patten's programme of
political reform.
On Friday, Mr Goodlad had made a public appeal to China that the two
countries should put this dispute behind them and get on with other
unresolved issues.
Two hours later, Mr Qian Qichen, China's foreign minister, rejected this
plea, in a stinging snub delivered as they met.
</TEXT>
