<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / Italian coalition partners trade blows: Events which have
led to the government's difficulties
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LANE and ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The agony of Italy's narrow defeat by Brazil in last night's World Cup final
in Los Angeles will deepen the gloom in Rome where a divided cabinet led by
prime minister Silvio Berlusconi nears a government crisis.
Angry exchanges between ministers about the decree to limit the use of
preventive detention, announced last week, have exposed the fragility and
self-interest which characterises the three-party coalition.
The populist Northern League, which has the largest single number of
deputies in parliament among the coalition members, is clearly embarrassed
by having put its signature to the decree as it has championed the rooting
out of corruption. Thus the sight of hundreds of businessmen, politicians
and officials being allowed to leave prison where they have been held on
preventive detention on corruption charges requires much explaining to
League supporters.
Mr Umberto Bossi, the League's leader, has offered full support to Mr
Roberto Maroni, who as minister for home affairs and deputy prime minister
is the party's senior representative in the cabinet. Mr Maroni has said he
was misled by cabinet colleagues about the contents of the decree and is
ready to resign his ministerial post. He also said he had been assured that
the use of a decree, which has immediate effect, rather than draft
legislation had been agreed with opposition parties.
His stance prompted Mr Giuliano Ferrara, minister for parliamentary
relations and press spokesman for Mr Berlusconi's government, to describe Mr
Maroni as politically infantile and amateur. Mr Ferrara belongs to Mr
Berlusconi's Forza Italia party.
Mr Maroni said he had been assured that the decree would not lead to the
release from prison of persons accused of corruption. However, it is hard to
believe that someone as astute as Mr Maroni was unaware of the implications
of the decree. All the political parties had been arguing over its contents
for at least two weeks.
The third coalition member, the neo-fascist MSI/National Alliance, has
equally prided itself on being an anti-corruption party. As a result Mr
Berlusconi has been isolated by his two partners, which are both concerned
to prevent their separate identities from being submerged under his Forza
Italia.
The coalition parties had been fully warned about the damaging consequences
in the eyes of the public of appearing to throw in the towel over the
corruption scandals. The Amato government nearly fell in 1993 when it tried
to push through what was seen as legislation pardoning the bulk of those
involved in the scandals.
There were demonstrations in Milan on Saturday against the decree, and in
favour of the team of investigating magistrates who resigned last week in
protest. Opinion polls taken after the decree seem to confirm that it is
unpopular.
Polls for the daily newspaper l'Unita show that nearly three-quarters
consider that the decree is wrong. Only one in seven believes that Mr
Berlusconi is right. More than three-quarters of the paper's sample support
Mr Antonio Di Pietro, the head of the team of investigating magistrates.
Under fire from the public, press, opposition parties and one of his
coalition members, Mr Berlusconi counter-attacked on Saturday, listing 12
points to justify the decree. Among these were the crowded conditions in
Italian prisons and the slow process of justice. Mr Berlusconi said that
remanding in custody should be an exception and only used for serious
offences.
He added that it was the duty of the prime minister to defend the weak and
that any modifications to the decree should reduce still further custody for
suspects. Motives other than concern for weaker citizens have, however, been
attributed to the commitment of Mr Berlusconi and Mr Alfredo Biondi, his
justice minister, to the decree.
Mr Maroni noted that one of the effects of the decree has been to put a
brake on investigations into corruption cases involving the fiscal police in
Milan, where important revelations had been thought imminent. One of the
first beneficiaries of the decree was Mr Biondi's former Liberal party
colleague, Mr Francesco De Lorenzo, former health minister.
The League will use all its influence to try to have the decree withdrawn.
Since it could use its strength in parliament to block it passing through
both houses, this is a real threat. Mr Berlusconi can use only one card -
the threat of early elections. Until now this threat has been credible
against his dissident partners because he has been riding high in the
opinion polls and would almost certainly improve his position at their
expense. But the impact of his conduct over the decree on public opinion
suggests he could now be weakened in the eyes of the electorate.
</TEXT>
