<HEADLINE>
FT  18 JUL 94 / Minister's threat puts Italian coalition in jeopardy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LANE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The survival of Italy's three-party coalition government led by Mr Silvio
Berlusconi was in danger last night, following the resignation threat of a
senior cabinet minister in a worsening row over a decree curbing the power
of magistrates.
Mr Roberto Maroni, minister for home affairs and deputy to Mr Berlusconi,
accused cabinet colleagues of trickery. He said he had been deceived about
the contents of the decree, promulgated last week, which has already led to
the release from jail of several well-known politicians and business people
accused of involvement in the 'tangentopoli', or bribesville, corruption
scandal.
Mr Berlusconi said yesterday evening that Mr Maroni's accusations were not
true. He demanded that his deputy make an unconditional withdrawal of the
accusations or resign.
The cabinet crisis and trial of strength between Mr Berlusconi and members
of his government come at the start of a week when the government's economic
policy is scheduled to be announced.
Mr Maroni, who said he should not have trusted his cabinet colleagues when
he sought assurances that the decree would not lead to the freeing of
suspects, told his party, the populist Northern League, that he was ready to
resign from government. However, the League's executive yesterday declined
Mr Maroni's offer to resign from Mr Berlusconi's cabinet. Mr Umberto Bossi,
the League's leader, said the deputy prime minister enjoyed the full
confidence and support of the party.
Mr Bossi said the decree should be withdrawn. He said the affair should not
be used as an excuse for fresh parliamentary elections, which Mr Berlusconi
has threatened to call on several occasions since assuming power two months
ago.
A firm line against corruption has been a fundamental part of the Northern
League's policy. Any softening of this position would threaten the standing
of Mr Bossi, and the release of those under investigation might be seen as a
sign of weakening.
Mr Bossi's call for withdrawal of the decree aims to reassure his party's
followers. Similar calls were made this weekend by the neo-fascist
MSI/National Alliance party, government partners with the League and Mr
Berlusconi's Forza Italia. In common with the League, the MSI takes a strong
line against corruption.
With two of the coalition members expressing serious misgivings about the
decree, Mr Berlusconi has been left isolated. Opinion polls suggest the
public is against the decree and supports the Milan investigating
magistrates who resigned in protest last week.
Ministers trade blows, Page 2
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
<XX>
