<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 94 / AT&amp;T's Dollars 12bn merger with McCaw cleared: Historic
telecoms deal beats last obstacle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
One of the biggest deals in US corporate history was given the go-ahead
yesterday when the Justice Department signed a consent decree allowing
American Telephone &amp; Telegraph to buy McCaw Cellular Communications for
Dollars 12.6bn (Pounds 8.1bn).
The all-share transaction will bring together the largest long-distance
telecommunications company in the US with the country's biggest operator in
the mobile phone business.
The deal was originally announced in August last year but had to be
investigated by the Justice Department to determine whether or not it could
be considered anti-competitive.
The department attached conditions to its consent to make sure the merged
company did not abuse its market position:
McCaw must allow equal access to its cellular systems to all long-distance
carriers, including AT&amp;T's competitors, so consumers can use the
long-distance carrier of their choice.
AT&amp;T must ensure that companies buying the cellular equipment AT&amp;T already
manufactures - many of them competitors of McCaw - are not disadvantaged by
the merger.
AT&amp;T said it was happy with the terms of the decree and that they did not
undermine the merger.
AT&amp;T invented cellular telephone technology more than 30 years ago and is a
big manufacturer of the equipment, but until now it has been unable to offer
mobile phone services.
One possible regulatory hurdle to the takeover was that, under the court
agreement which broke up the old Bell System company and gave birth to AT&amp;T
and the local telephone companies, AT&amp;T became a long-distance carrier. The
so-called Baby Bells were given the local phone markets.
Some Baby Bells said it would be unfair to allow AT&amp;T to enter their markets
through the acquisition of McCaw because the break-up agreement forbids them
from entering the long-distance market. But AT&amp;T said the overwhelming
majority of local calls would continue to be made through ordinary
telephones and it was not interested in competing in local telephone
markets.
Although McCaw is heavily indebted and loss-making, AT&amp;T wants to acquire it
because it regards mobile phones as the way of the future.
The deal still has to be agreed by the US district court in Washington, and
there will be a 60-day period for comments. But it is unlikely to face any
further big hurdles, and AT&amp;T said yesterday its would put its merger plans
into operation very soon.
US West poised for deal, Page 11
</TEXT>
