<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JUL 94 / Seoul uneasy as funeral put off
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BURTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
North Korea early today postponed the state funeral of Kim Il-sung - a
surprise move that caused some concern among South Korean officials.
The North said the former president's funeral, planned for tomorrow, would
be put off until Tuesday to allow more mourners to stream past his body,
lying in state in Pyongyang.
Officials in Seoul fear one result of the postponement may be to fan unrest
in the South, where there is increasingly bitter debate about how the Seoul
government should respond to the death a week ago of the North's Communist
leader.
The Seoul authorities have announced a crackdown on left-wing organisations
planning mourning ceremonies. This follows the firebombing of six police
stations in Seoul on Thursday by radical students protesting at the arrest
of student organisers for praising President Kim. Student organisations have
said they will send groups with condolences to Pyongyang, after North Korea
announced it would let South Koreans wanting to pay homage cross the heavily
fortified demilitarised zone separating the two Koreas.
North Korea yesterday resumed propaganda attacks against the South. It
criticised South Korean President Kim Young-sam for placing troops and
police on alert.
'Despite the fact that even the US president and Japanese prime minister
expressed their regrets over the death of President Kim Il-sung, only Kim
Young-sam. . . is acting recklessly,' declared the state-controlled Radio
Pyongyang.
South Korean officials have privately criticised President Bill Clinton for
offering condolences over Mr Kim's death in a diplomatic gesture to maintain
US dialogue with the new North Korean leadership.
</TEXT>
